Bayesian First Aid Examples

binom.test

A classical binomial test:

library(BayesianFirstAid)
binom.test(x = 16, n = 20)

## 
##  Exact binomial test
## 
## data:  16 and 20
## number of successes = 16, number of trials = 20, p-value = 0.01182
## alternative hypothesis: true probability of success is not equal to 0.5
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.5634 0.9427
## sample estimates:
## probability of success 
##                    0.8

Prepend binom.test by bayes. to run the Bayesian “version”.

bayes.binom.test(x = 16, n = 20)

## 
##  Bayesian first aid binomial test
## 
## data: 16 and 20
## number of successes = 16, number of trials = 20
## Estimated relative frequency of success:
##   0.771 
## 95% credible interval:
##   0.589 0.926 
## The relative frequency of success is more than 0.5 by a probability of 0.996 
## and less than 0.5 by a probability of 0.004

The idea is to respect the arguments to the original binom.test as far as possible. For example, setting p and conf.level as in…

binom.test(x = 16, n = 20, p = 0.75, conf.level = 0.8)

## 
##  Exact binomial test
## 
## data:  16 and 20
## number of successes = 16, number of trials = 20, p-value = 0.7977
## alternative hypothesis: true probability of success is not equal to 0.75
## 80 percent confidence interval:
##  0.6393 0.9098
## sample estimates:
## probability of success 
##                    0.8

… is respected by bayes.binom.test:

bayes.binom.test(x = 16, n = 20, p = 0.75, conf.level = 0.8)

## 
##  Bayesian first aid binomial test
## 
## data: 16 and 20
## number of successes = 16, number of trials = 20
## Estimated relative frequency of success:
##   0.771 
## 80% credible interval:
##   0.674 0.895 
## The relative frequency of success is more than 0.75 by a probability of 0.622 
## and less than 0.75 by a probability of 0.378

By assigning the result of bayes.binom.test to a variable we can get some more useful info by calling plot for looking at the posterior (and perhaps a posterior predictive check), summary for a more extensive summary than the standard print out above, and diagnostics for MCMC diagnostics. The idea is that the behavior of these functions should be consistent for all the bayes.*.test functions. 

(fit <- bayes.binom.test(x = 16, n = 20))

## 
##  Bayesian first aid binomial test
## 
## data: 16 and 20
## number of successes = 16, number of trials = 20
## Estimated relative frequency of success:
##   0.775 
## 95% credible interval:
##   0.598 0.923 
## The relative frequency of success is more than 0.5 by a probability of 0.995 
## and less than 0.5 by a probability of 0.005

plot(fit)


summary(fit)

##   Data
## number of successes = 16, number of trials = 20
## 
##   Model parameters and generated quantities
## theta: The relative frequency of success
## x_pred: Predicted number of successes in a replication
## 
##   Measures
##          mean    sd  HDIlo  HDIup %<comp %>comp
## theta   0.775 0.086  0.598  0.923  0.005  0.995
## x_pred 15.468 2.526 11.000 20.000  0.001  0.999
## 
## 'HDIlo' and 'HDIup' are the limits of a 95% HDI credible interval.
## '%<comp' and '%>comp' are the probabilities of the respective parameter being
## smaller or larger than 0.5.
## 
##   Quantiles
##         q2.5%   q25% median   q75% q97.5%
## theta   0.586  0.719  0.784  0.839  0.919
## x_pred 10.000 14.000 16.000 17.000 20.000

diagnostics(fit)

## 
## Iterations = 1:500
## Thinning interval = 1 
## Number of chains = 3 
## Sample size per chain = 500 
## 
##   Diagnostic measures
##          mean    sd mcmc_se n_eff Rhat
## theta   0.775 0.086   0.002  1841    1
## x_pred 15.468 2.526   0.065  1500    1
## 
## mcmc_se: the estimated standard error of the MCMC approximation of the mean.
## n_eff: a crude measure of effective MCMC sample size.
## Rhat: the potential scale reduction factor (at convergence, Rhat=1).
## 
##   Model parameters and generated quantities
## theta: The relative frequency of success
## x_pred: Predicted number of successes in a replication

Of course, in the case of bayes.binom.test the MCMC diagnostics might be a bit silly…

By asking for the model.code we get a print out of a script that runs the same analysis as bayes.binom.test. This could be copied into an R-script to study how it works or to modify it further.

model.code(fit)

## function (x, n, n.chains = 3, n.iter = 500) 
## {
##     model_string <- "\n    model {\n      x ~ dbinom(theta, n)\n      theta ~ dbeta(1, 1)\n      x_pred ~ dbinom(theta, n)\n    }\n  "
##     mcmc_samples <- run_jags(model_string, data = list(x = x, 
##         n = n), inits = list(theta = (x + 1)/(n + 2)), params = c("theta", 
##         "x_pred"), n.chains = n.chains, n.adapt = 0, n.update = 0, 
##         n.iter = n.iter, thin = 1)
##     mcmc_samples
## }
## <environment: namespace:BayesianFirstAid>

t.test

The alternative for the t.test is of course BEST.

x <- rnorm(n = 30, mean = 2, sd = 5)
t.test(x)

## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  x
## t = 1.97, df = 29, p-value = 0.05842
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.06713  3.59610
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##     1.764

bayes.t.test(x)

## 
##  Bayesian estimation supersedes the t test (BEST)
## 
## data: x
## 
##   Estimates [95% credible interval]
## mean of x: 1.737 [-0.114, 3.53]
## sd of x: 4.937 [3.48, 6.507]
## 
## The mean is more than 0 by a probability of 0.966 
## and less than 0 by a probability of 0.034

bayes.t.test also respects the arguments of the original t.test.

y <- rnorm(n = 30, mean = 10, sd = 5)
bayes.t.test(x, y, mu = 1, conf.level = 0.5)

## 
##  Bayesian estimation supersedes the t test (BEST)
## 
## data: x and y
## 
##   Estimates [50% credible interval]
## mean of x: 1.792 [1.175, 2.389]
## mean of y: 10.9 [10.42, 11.48]
## difference of the means: -9.107 [-9.829, -8.161]
## sd of x: 5.011 [4.362, 5.261]
## sd of y: 4.233 [3.683, 4.474]
## 
## The difference of the means is more than 1 by a probability of 0.001 
## and less than 1 by a probability of 0.999

Or even…

# Creating 'paired' data
d <- data.frame(x = rnorm(n = 30, mean = 10, sd = 5), group = rep(c("A", "B"), 
    15))

bayes.t.test(x ~ group, paired = T, data = d)

## 
##  Bayesian estimation supersedes the t test (BEST)
## 
## data: x by group
## 
##   Estimates [95% credible interval]
## mean paired difference: 0.082 [-3.154, 3.798]
## sd of the paired differences: 6.292 [3.886, 9.052]
## 
## The mean difference is more than 0 by a probability of 0.516 
## and less than 0 by a probability of 0.484

The same generic functions (plot, summary, diagnostics) works for all fitted models from bayes.t.test.

Output one sample bayes.t.test
